Here’s the thing… from 2018 to 2023 I’ve always had one similar goal. Which was to be active and live a healthy lifestyle. I’ve continued to do just that. But here’s the kicker, my body has changed in some way every year. And it’ll continue to change naturally as we get older. Your goals of having that body you had in high-school or college are dead. Your body is in no way shape or form that 16/18yr old you once were. Let it go and focus on the body you have NOW. Work on feeling good in your current body and moving because you want the benefits of living a healthy lifestyle.

Aesthetic goals are FINE, I’ve been working on building my booty now since 2020. But focusing on aesthetics to have a body that you no longer naturally have is just not realistic. Your goals need to be achievable and doable. Results take time, focus on the current you and accepting the simple fact that our bodies will continuously change.

Sometimes I jump for the bar, other times I use an elevated surface. Whichever you choose is fine. As a fitness coach though, I encourage my clients to stand on some kind of elevated surface. The goal is to minimize the risk of injury within the gym. After seeing a girl land on her back and get the wind knocked out of her. I don’t opt for jumping up to the bar unless you’re VERY comfortable with it. Also I feel like the jumping part is what detours a lot of people from even trying pull-ups. So here’s a few benefits of why you should use a stool instead of jumping for the bar…. From a fitness coaches perspective:

👉 Improved Form: Start your pull-ups from a stable position, ensuring proper form and maximizing muscle activation.

👉 Reduced Joint Strain: Skip the jumping and minimize stress on your shoulders and wrists for a safer, injury-free workout.

👉 Targeted Muscle Engagement: Get closer to the bar and focus on activating your back, shoulders, and arms effectively.

👉 Increased Repetitions and Progression: Take advantage of the stool assist to perform more reps and steadily build strength over time.

Sore muscles don't always mean a great workout. Here's why:  1️⃣ Soreness ≠ Progress: It's a common misconception. Soreness doesn't indicate a more effective workout. It's often due to new stress on muscles, not progress.  2️⃣ Factors at Play: Multiple factors cause soreness, like eccentric contractions, microdamage, inflammation, and byproducts. These don't directly relate to muscle growth or strength gains.  3️⃣ Individual Variations: Responses to soreness differ. Some feel it with light workouts, others don't with intense sessions. Everyone's body adapts differently.  4️⃣ Focus on Overload: Progressive overload matters more. Gradually increase demands on muscles to stimulate growth, regardless of soreness.  5️⃣ Listen to Your Body: Look for improved endurance, strength, form, and performance. Use these as indicators of a good workout.  🔑 Soreness isn't a reliable measure of success. Stay focused on long-term goals, train smart, and let progress guide your fitness journey!

Pull-ups hold a special place in my heart. They were one of the first skills I decided to focus on when I started my gym journey back in 2014/15. I was inspired by a guy at the gym and thought, “Can I do that?” So, I gave it a shot and managed to do 3 not-so-perfect ones, but I tried. And from that day forward, I’ve been hooked on pull-ups.

Here are 3 exercises I’ve consistently done since then, with various variations on the side, but let’s save that for another chat.

💪 Dead Hangs: Besides pulling myself up, I realized that holding my own weight for an extended period was a challenge. Dead hangs became my go-to to enhance grip and arm strength.

🏋️ Inverted Barbell Rows: Next came the challenge of pulling my body weight up. Inverted barbell rows are versatile and adaptable to your skill level. They help you build the muscles necessary for those pull-ups.

🔥 Assisted Pull-ups: Bands or the assisted machine were game-changers for me. I’m all about form and technique. Focusing on the mind-muscle connection over reps significantly improved my form.

In case you were wondering what those workouts look like :)

1️⃣ Dead Hangs: Dead hangs are a simple yet effective exercise for building grip strength and improving shoulder stability. Find a sturdy pull-up bar, grasp it with an overhand grip (palms facing away), and allow your body to hang freely. Keep your arms fully extended, engaging your lats, forearms, and shoulders. Hang for as long as you can, aiming to increase your time gradually.

2️⃣ Inverted Barbell Rows: Inverted barbell rows are excellent for targeting your back, shoulders, and biceps. Lie on your back beneath a barbell placed on a rack, play around with the height until you find something that works for you. Reach up and grip the bar with your hands spaced slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Keeping your body straight, pull your chest up toward the barbell, squeezing your shoulder blades together. Lower yourself back down and repeat for a set of reps.

3️⃣ Assisted Pull-ups: If you’re working your way up to doing full pull-ups, assisted pull-ups are a great stepping stone. You can use an assisted pull-up machine or a resistance band. Attach the band or set the machine to provide support, making the exercise more manageable. Grab the pull-up bar with an overhand grip, hang freely, then pull your chin up towards the bar. This exercise primarily targets your lats, biceps, and upper back muscles.

Hope this helps :)💕
